'''Liberty University''' is a private, non-profit Christian university located in [[Lynchburg, Virginia]], [[United States]], that describes itself as a Christian academic community. Liberty's annual enrollment includes 13,800 residential students and over 100,000 online students as of May 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/news/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=125545 |title=About Liberty &#124; Liberty University Quick Facts &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/news/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=56836 |title=Liberty Online now 80,000 strong &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2015-04-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.newsadvance.com/news/2012/may/16/five-years-after-death-jerry-falwell-sr-growth-boo-ar-1917125/ |title=Five years after death of Jerry Falwell Sr., growth booming at Liberty &#124; The News & Advance |publisher=.newsadvance.com |date= |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref> When including the number of people taking its online courses, LU is the largest  [[Evangelicalism|Evangelical Christian]] university in the world, the nation's largest private non-profit university and 7th largest four-year university, and the largest university in Virginia.<ref>[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/06/02/AR2010060203280.html Liberty University reviewing claims that seminary president lied about his past] [[Washington Post]], Michelle Boorstein. June 2, 2010</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=McDonald |first=Michael |url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-02-27/god-a-click-away-as-web-courses-fuel-falwell-s-college.html |title=God a Click Away as Web Courses Fuel Falwell’s College |publisher=Bloomberg |date=2013-02-27 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wukman |first=Alex |url=http://www.onlinecolleges.net/2012/06/13/liberty-university-online-enrollment-reaches-80000/ |title=Liberty University Online Enrollment Reaches 80,000 |publisher=Online Colleges |date=2012-06-13 |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref>

Liberty's athletic teams compete in [[Division I (NCAA)|Division I]] of the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association|NCAA]] and are collectively known as the [[Liberty Flames]]. They compete in the [[Big South Conference]].

==History==
The university was founded as ''Lynchburg Baptist College'' in 1971 by [[Jerry Falwell]], who was also Senior Pastor of [[Thomas Road Baptist Church]]. The name was changed to ''Liberty Baptist College'' in 1976 before settling on its current name, ''Liberty University'', in 1984, when it obtained [[university]] status.

Liberty University describes itself as a Christian academic community. Its stated mission and aims emphasize both the intellectual and spiritual development of the institution's students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?PID=6899|title=About Liberty - Purpose/Mission|accessdate=2007-09-19}}</ref> Students are held to ''The Liberty Way'', a code of conduct.

==Campus==
[[Image:Demoss.JPG|thumb|200px|DeMoss Learning Center at Liberty University]] 
[[Image:Vines Center.JPG|thumb|200px|Liberty University Vines Center]]

===Main, East and North campuses===
Liberty University's Campus East housing complex consists of 30 multi-story apartment style [[dormitories]], the last six of which were completed in 2007. Rooms in these dormitories have their own kitchens, [[living room]] and private baths. A [[Community centre|clubhouse]] offers a [[swimming pool]], [[billiards]] room, and a private theater. A tunnel connecting the east and west ends of the campus was completed in 2004. A second tunnel was completed in May 2014, and provides pedestrian passage under the [[Norfolk Southern Railway]] and access to nearby shopping opportunities. In addition, a campus bus/shuttle system was added in the fall of 2006, providing transportation both on and off campus until midnight most evenings.

The {{convert|90000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} LaHaye Student Center, has a lounge, basketball courts, cardio and weight rooms, cafe, multi-purpose rooms, aerobic rooms and other amenities.<ref>[http://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?PID=7014 LaHaye Student Center - Official Page - Liberty University]{{dead link|date=September 2011}}</ref> The adjacent Tilley Center has TV lounges, game tables, pool room, and social areas, as well as a stage for student performances, bands and small concerts. Other projects include a {{convert|60|mi|adj=on}} [[mountain bike]] trail system, a [[motorcross]] facility, [[paintball]] fields, 3D [[archery]] range, intramural sports program and club sports, including lacrosse and [[ice hockey]], which plays in an ice rink donated by Drs. [[Tim LaHaye|Tim]] and [[Beverly LaHaye]], and a new indoor soccer facility.

During the spring of 2007, a secondary practice facility for the Liberty volleyball program was opened as part of a new, on-campus training complex. The existing $750,000 facility on Campus East houses the volleyball coaches’ offices and a team room, and serves as the team’s practice facility whenever the Vines Center and Schilling Center are unavailable.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertyflames.com/index.cfm?PID=21864 |title=Volleyball - Campus East Volleyball Facility |publisher=Liberty Flames |date=2014-02-04 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref>

[[File:Snowflex 3.jpg|thumb|left|Top of the Snowflex synthetic ski slope overlooking Liberty Mountain Snowflex Centre]]Construction was completed in August 2009 on the Liberty Mountain Snowflex Centre, a synthetic ski slope featuring [[Snowflex]]; the Centre was designed by England’s Briton Engineering. It includes beginner, intermediate and advanced slopes, and is the first of its kind in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/11/27/AR2009112701856.html|title=In Lynchburg, a skiing adventure, minus the snow|accessdate=2010-11-10 | work=The Washington Post|first=Becky|last=Krystal|date=2009-11-29}}</ref>

On September 24, 2010, Liberty opened the new Tower Theater, with seating for up to 640 people.  For the 2010-11 theater season, the Theater Department opened with ''Hairspray,'' and closed in Spring 2011 with ''The Phantom of the Opera.'' The theatre includes balcony seating, an orchestra pit, catwalks, a fly tower, a box office and {{convert|12000|sqft}} of support area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/news/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=19836 |title=BUILDING UP: Construction projects keep campus abuzz this summer &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2010-06-15 |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref> The tower was originally part of a cell phone plant. BCWH Architects, which designed the adaptation of the tower as a theatre, won first place at the [[ASID]]'s annual IDEAs for the Contract Institutional Category.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/news/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=40842 |title=Tower Theater designers earn award &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>

In August 2011, Liberty announced a 120 million dollar campus expansion. The expansion includes more dorms, greener space, and more academic buildings allowing the campus to hold 20,000 resident students.<ref name="liberty1">{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/news/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=37241 |title=Campus transformation planned &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2011-08-25 |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref>

In January 2012, Liberty University's Department of Theatre Arts announced the formation of a professional theater company to occupy the Tower Theater. The Alluvion Stage Company will hire professional actors to perform alongside the students, and the sets and costumes will meet professional standards. Department Chair Linda Nell Cooper said about the new company: "Alluvion, meaning overflow, will aim to enrich, educate and entertain the community by providing a superior theater experience in a wholesome family environment."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=45653 |title=Theatre Arts Department launches professional stage company &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2012-01-12 |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>

Liberty University is scheduled to open a new Observatory Center in the Spring of 2013 next to Liberty's Equestrian Center.  Lee Beaumont, Vice President of Auxiliary Services, says this dome will be a classroom that can fit up to 20 people.  It will house a {{convert|20|in|adj=on}} RC Optical Systems Truss Ritchey-Chrétien high-quality research telescope and several Celestron CPC 800 8-inch Schmidt-Cassegrain telescopes that will be on pedestal, able to roll out under a roof. Astronomy Professor Van Eaton says new observatory serves three purposes: instruction, public nights and research.  Student Activities will control the use of the observatory, and all students are welcome to use this building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.libertychampion.com/2012/09/liberty-to-launch-new-observatory-center/ |title=Liberty to launch new observatory center |publisher=The Liberty Champion |date= |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref>

===Libraries & Museums===

====Integrated Learning Resource Center====
The Integrated Learning Resource Center (ILRC) has three components:  the Curriculum Library, Computer Labs, and Media Services.  The library contains the following: around 250,000 paper volumes, over 150,000 e-books, more than 97,000 unique electronic and print periodical titles, and more than 200 electronic databases.<ref name="ReferenceA">{{cite web|url=https://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?PID=4785 |title=Library &#124; ILRC - What is the ILRC? &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>  Students have access to the ILRC. Freshmen have a mandatory session in the Curriculum Library to assess basic research skills.<ref name="ReferenceA"/> Education students can make use of textbooks and teaching material. DVDs, CDs, and videos are available for audio visual use.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/informationservices/ilrc/library/curriculumlibrary/index.cfm?PID=409 |title=Curriculum Library &#124; Official Page &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref> Sixteen classroom labs contain more than 470 computers, with more than 350 computers in open spaces, and over 250 computers throughout the campus.  All of these computers have a high-speed internet connection.<ref name="ReferenceA"/>  Specific tutor sessions are available and posted at the ILRC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/informationservices/ilrc/labs/index.cfm?PID=9326 |title=ILRC Labs &#124; ILRC Computer Labs - Tutors &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>  Media Services includes classroom technical support, Smart Board support, basic video duplication, and equipment for classroom projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?pid=407 |title=Media Services &#124; Official Page &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>

Liberty University students are provided academic counseling and support services through the Center for Academic Support and Advising Services (CASAS). CASAS contains new student orientation support, professional academic advising, continuing education counseling, tutoring and testing services, and career placement services.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/academics/casas/index.cfm?PID=110 |title=Center for Academic Support and Advising Services &#124; Official Page &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref> A component of CASAS is the Bruckner Learning Center, which seeks to "provide University-wide academic support services for all students and faculty in general and special needs students in particular".<ref>[https://www.liberty.edu/media/1171/BLC%20Brochure%20-%20Front%20and%20Inside%20Combined.pdf ]{{dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref> The Bruckner Learning Center offers courses in transitioning from high school to college, college learning strategies, advanced reading and vocabulary development, and developmental math to help students succeed in the college environment. Additionally, in 2010, Liberty University opened the Osborne Assistive Learning Technology Center in the A. Pierre Guillermin Library, which is a learning and testing center for special needs students. The lab works in with the Bruckner Learning Center and contains assistive software, such as text-to-speech and speech-to-text programs for visually impaired or reading disabled students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/news/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=16346 |title=Alumnus contributes lab for special needs students &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2010-03-04 |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>

====Jerry Falwell Library====
In January 2014, Liberty University opened the new Jerry Falwell Library. The four-story, 170,000-square-foot building is located behind the Vines Center.<ref>{{cite web|author=Amy Trent |url=http://www.newsadvance.com/news/local/falwell-library-opens-to-the-public/article_20ba4aa0-7e6d-11e3-84e9-0019bb30f31a.html |title=Falwell Library opens to the public - NewsAdvance.com : News - Lynchburg, Virginia Area |publisher=NewsAdvance.com |date= |accessdate=2015-04-16}}</ref> The library features a robot-assisted storage and retrieval system for over 250,000 archived items, with room for another 170,000. The robot locates requested items within a large storage room and delivers the items to the front desk. There are also 150 public computers throughout the building for electronic archive research. The library features group study rooms, writable walls, balconies, terraces and a vegetative roof. The entrance to the library is highlighted by a 24&nbsp;ft media wall powered by three Microsoft Kinect units and integrated using a custom program. The media wall uses motion-sensor technology to enable visitors to scroll through university news, browse pictures contributed from students and learn about upcoming university events.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.onwindows.com/Article/media-wall-helps-increase-engagement-at-liberty-university-library-40778#.U9sNBfldXd0/ |title=Media wall helps increase engagement at Liberty University library; OnWindows |publisher=onwindows.com |date= |accessdate=2014-07-28}}</ref> The $50 million library is part of a larger $500 million building and expansion plan announced by Liberty University.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsadvance.com/news/local/falwell-library-opens-to-the-public/article_20ba4aa0-7e6d-11e3-84e9-0019bb30f31a.html/ |title=Falwell library opens to the public; The News & Advance |publisher=.newadvance.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wdbj7.com/news/local/liberty-university-dedicates-jerry-falwell-library/23948576 |title=Liberty University dedicates Jerry Falwell Library; wdbj7 |publisher=..wdbj7.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-10}}</ref>

====National Civil War Chaplains Museum====
The National Civil War Chaplains Museum contains exhibits of clergy members and religious activity during the [[American Civil War|Civil War]] era.  It is the only [[museum]] in the nation devoted to this purpose.  The mission of the museum is to “educate the public about the role of [[chaplains]], [[priests]], and [[rabbis]] and religious organizations in the Civil War; to promote the continuing study of the many methods of dissemination of religious doctrine and moral teachings during the War; to preserve religious [[Artifact (archaeology)|artifacts]], and to present interpretive programs that show the influence of religion on the lives of political and military personnel.”<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chaplainsmuseum.org/i/?page_id=166 |title=We'll Be Back! |publisher=Chaplainsmuseum.org |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref> A 501(c)(3) organization, the museum rents space from Liberty University’s DeMoss Center. It has 10,000 square feet, with a 50-seat video theatre, archive displays, a research library, and book store.

The museum features [[Catholic]], [[Protestant]], [[Jewish]] chaplains (including [[African American]] chaplains), publications, and artifacts from both the [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] and [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] militaries. There are several areas in the museum that are given special attention including:
*The role of the [[United States Christian Commission]], which is the forerunner to today’s [[USO]] and [[Red Cross]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discoverlynchburg.org/220_attractions_national-civil-war-chaplains-museum |title=Local Attractions, National Civil War Chaplains Museum |publisher=Discover Lynchburg |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>
*“The relationship of religion to political and military leaders, common soldiers, and the public in the North and South.”<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.civilwarnews.com/archive/articles/Chaplains.htm |title=New Museum Will Honor Civil War Chaplains |publisher=Civilwarnews.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>

Two new exhibits have been added to the museum as of 2012: "a “mourning room” with period furniture and decorations (including a cross formed from the woven hair of dead Confederate soldiers), and an exhibit on Civil War sharpshooters featuring Rev. Lorenzo Barbour, chaplain to the Confederate Berdan’s Sharpshooters."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.newsadvance.com/news/2012/may/23/darrell-laurant-civil-war-chaplain-museum-feature--ar-1938538/ |title=Darrell Laurant: Civil War chaplain museum to feature two new exhibits &#124; The News & Advance |publisher=.newsadvance.com |date=2012-05-23 |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref>

In September 2012, Liberty University hosted the 16th annual Civil War Seminar. Titled "1862-The Rise of Lee and Grant", the seminar featured presentations on many different Civil War issues, highlighted by lectures on Grant's Mississippi and Vicksburg Campaigns and Lee's Seven Days' Campaign. The event also featured an online simulation of the Battle of Antietam.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/news/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=64555 |title=Liberty to host 2012 Civil War Seminar &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2012-09-17 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref>

====Carter Glass Mansion====
The Carter Glass Mansion is a historic home originally built in 1923 by U.S. Senator [[Carter Glass]] a newspaper publisher, politician and U.S. Secretary of the Treasury under President Woodrow Wilson as well as Chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee and President Pro Tempore of the Senate during President Roosevelt's era.<ref name="dhr.virginia.gov">{{cite web|url=http://www.dhr.virginia.gov/registers/Cities/Lynchburg/118-0210_Montview_1987_Final_Nomination.pdf |format=PDF |title=National Register of Historic Place : Inventory - Nomination Form |publisher=Dhr.virginia.gov |accessdate=2015-04-16}}</ref> Also known as Montview, the mansion is part of the National Register of Historic Places and is a state landmark. The {{convert|1.7|acre|ha|adj=on}} estate consists of a {{frac|1|1|2}}-story main building flanked by slightly smaller ells. The {{convert|18|in|cm|adj=on}} walls are constructed of quartz fieldstone quarried from the property and the mansion is covered with a grey gambrel roof.<ref name="dhr.virginia.gov"/> The estate was purchased by Liberty University in the late 1970s as the headquarters of the university administration, including the main office of university founder Jerry Falwell. One of the many reasons for the estate’s continued fame is that Falwell died at his desk at the Carter Glass Mansion on May 15, 2007, and his office has been preserved in the same condition ever since. Falwell was buried on the lawn of the mansion and a memorial to Falwell was placed there, overlooking the rest of the campus. The estate now serves mostly as a tourist site for the historically restored mansion as well as the Falwell office, while the upstairs portion of the mansion has been converted to a bed and breakfast for Liberty University guests.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.newsadvance.com/news/2008/may/15/falwells_family_preserving_his_office_at_carter_gl-ar-224228/ |title=Falwell's family preserving his office at Carter Glass mansion &#124; The News & Advance |publisher=.newsadvance.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>

==Academics==
[[File:Liberty University C-172.jpg|thumb|Liberty University School of Aeronautics Cessna 172]]
[[Image:DeMoss Hall.JPG|200px|thumb|Liberty's DeMoss Hall, the campus's main academic building exhibiting Jeffersonian architecture.]]
As of August 2011, Liberty offers 148 residential and online undergraduate programs and among those offered are  [[Aeronautics]],<ref name="liberty.edu">{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/academics/arts-sciences/aeronautics/ |title=University Offices - Official Page - Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref> [[Philosophy of religion|Philosophy of Religion]], English, [[Worship music|Worship & Music Studies]], [[Business]], [[Criminal Justice]], [[Education]], [[Nursing]], [http://www.liberty.edu/academics/index.cfm?PID=541 School of Engineering and Computational Sciences], and [http://www.liberty.edu/academics/religion/seminary/ Theological Seminary]. Liberty also offers 87 graduate programs and 11 doctoral programs within the residential and online programs.<ref name="Liberty University">{{cite web|url=https://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?PID=6925 |title=About Liberty |accessdate=2011-10-18}}</ref>

===Liberty Baptist Theological Seminary===
Likely the most notable of Liberty University's schools is the Liberty Baptist Theological Seminary (LBTS).  It was founded in 1973, and now offers various degrees for both academic and vocational endeavors.  The degrees available are the Master of Divinity (M.Div.), Master of Religious Education (including Military Chaplaincy), Master of Theology (Th.M.), Master of Arts in Marketplace Chaplaincy, Master of Arts in Pastoral Counseling, Master of Arts in Religion (M.A.R.), Master of Arts in Theological Studies (M.A.T.S.), Master of Arts in Worship Studies, Doctor of Ministry (D.Min.), Doctor of Philosophy in Theology and Apologetics(Ph.D.).  Some of the degrees are available to be completed online, others require residential study, while some are available in both formats.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/academics/religion/seminary/index.cfm?PID=15337 |title=Degree Programs &#124; Liberty Baptist Theological Seminary and Graduate School |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2014-02-04 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref>

====Center for Ministry Training====
The Center for Ministry Training is the practical experience requirement for LBTS students.  The requirements are much like internships for other programs with a religious aspect involved in the experience.  Specifically, the CMT includes Ministry Impact and Supervised Field Ministry Experience (SFME).  Ministry Impact asks a Ministry Specialist to speak on practical aspects of ministry in the world today.  Additionally, "[t]he main requirement for completing SFME is completing a minimum of 40 hours of field ministry during each semester."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/academics/ministrytraining/index.cfm?PID=4665 |title=Center for Ministry Training &#124; Official Page &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2014-02-04 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/academics/ministrytraining/index.cfm?PID=11193 |title=Center for Ministry Training &#124; Ministry Impact &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2014-02-04 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref><ref>[http://www.liberty.edu/academics/ministrytraining/index.cfm?PID=2949 ]{{dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref>

===Zaki Gordon Cinematic Arts Center===
Liberty University now offers a Bachelor of Science in Cinematic Arts Degree.  This program is offered in the new Zaki Gordon Cinematic Arts Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/aboutliberty/index.cfm?PID=25725 |title=About Liberty &#124; Feature - Cinematic Arts Program &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref> "The B.S. in Communication Studies with a concentration in Cinematic Arts is a 2-year cohort program that students enter in their junior year."  A minor is also offered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/academics/communications/cinematicarts/index.cfm?PID=25536 |title=Cinematic Arts &#124; Program Information &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref> The disciplines taught include the following:  Producing, Directing, Screenwriting, Cinematography, Production Design, Post-Production, General Production, Documentary, Narrative.  Around 1.5 million dollars was spent on professional equipment.<ref name="newsadvance1">{{cite web|url=http://www2.newsadvance.com/news/2012/mar/31/liberty-university-debuts-first-round-classes-new--ar-1807541/ |title=Liberty University debuts first round of classes in new film school &#124; The News & Advance |publisher=.newsadvance.com |date=2012-03-31 |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref> Guest speakers come to offer their experience to the students in the classrooms as well as in a workshop to the public.  Examples of speakers that were featured in 2012 include Dan Gordon (Screenwriter), Randall Wallace (screenwriter), Sterling Anderson (Screenwriter), and Shawn Nelson (Acting Coach).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/academics/communications/cinematicarts/index.cfm?PID=25538 |title=Cinematic Arts &#124; Cinematic Arts Speakers &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref>

In the fall semester of 2012, 40 students will be accepted as the inaugural class to major in Cinematic Arts, eventually expanding the number of accepted students to 160.  "During the first year, students will produce and direct a short film and write a full-length screenplay. They also will learn how to produce films for non-conventional and emerging platforms, such as cell phones and YouTube."<ref name="newsadvance1"/> The executive director of the Zaki Gordon Cinematic Arts Center is Stephan Schultze, a Hollywood veteran who is known for movies such as ''[[Far and Away]]''.<ref name="newsadvance1"/> "Chancellor Jerry Falwell, Jr. said the decision was spurred by the interest shown by current School of Communication students and is inline with Liberty’s commitment to future expansion of academic offerings and academic facilities."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.wdbj7.com/2011-05-02/liberty-university_29497597 |title=Liberty University plans new Cinematic Arts Center - WDBJ7 |publisher=Articles.wdbj7.com |date=2011-05-02 |accessdate=2012-07-10}}</ref>

The second year culminates in a large-scale theatrical project and a film festival. Students also will be required to write a business and fundraising plan for producing their own screenplay.

===College of Osteopathic Medicine===
On October 3, 2011, a 12 million dollar grant was sanctioned by the Virginia Tobacco Commission to build a college of [[Osteopathic medicine in the United States|osteopathic medicine]] and expand the health sciences school.<ref name="luonline">{{cite web|url=http://www.luonline.com/index.cfm?PID=19109&MID=38541 |title=Tobacco Commission approves grant for medical school &#124; Liberty University Online |publisher=Luonline.com |date= |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>  According to the grant, Liberty University must match the 12 million dollars for construction and equipment.<ref name="roanoke">{{cite web|last=Bruyn |first=Sarah |url=http://www.roanoke.com/business/wb/298456 |title=Liberty University's medical school recommended for $12 million grant |publisher=Roanoke.com |date=2011-09-16 |accessdate=2012-06-08}}</ref>  This grant is the second largest ever authorized to a medical school by the Virginia Tobacco Commission.<ref name="luonline"/>  A new 140,000-square-foot building will house the osteopathic medical school,<ref name=NewSchoolDO>{{cite news|last=Schierhorn|first=Carolyn|title=New school aims to meld Christian worldview, dedication to underserved|url=http://thedo.osteopathic.org/?p=166821|newspaper=The DO|date=February 5, 2014}}</ref> at an estimated cost of 40 million dollars.  Liberty University plans to enroll the first class in the Fall of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=College of Osteopathic Medicine receives provisional accreditation|url=http://www.liberty.edu/lucom/index.cfm?PID=28248&MID=96875|publisher=Liberty University}}</ref>  "The new facilities are located in Campbell County near the intersection of US-460 and US-29 near the Lynchburg Airport."<ref name="luonline"/>  The college currently holds provisional accreditation from the [[American Osteopathic Association]] through the [[American Osteopathic Association]] [[Commission on Osteopathic College Accreditation]], with opportunity for full accreditation in 2018.<ref>{{cite web|title=Liberty University College of Osteopathic Medicine|url=http://www.aacom.org/about/colleges/Documents/2014%20CIB%20Supplement-Liberty.pdf|work=AACOM infobook|publisher=American Association of Colleges of Osteopathic Medicine}}</ref>

===School of Law===
See [[Liberty University School of Law]].

===School of Music===
In September 2012, Liberty University announced that it will be combining the Department of Music and Humanities with the Department of Worship and Music Studies to form a new School of Music. The school of music will have 32 full-time and 24 adjunct faculty members separated into two distinct centers. The Center for Music and Performing Arts will focus on music education and performance technique, while the Center for Music and Worship will seek to train skilled musicians as worship leaders and specialists within the Christian music industry. The School of Music will be located in a new building being constructed across from the Arthur S. DeMoss Learning Center. The faculty from the School of Music are collaborating with the construction team to optimize the building to their needs. The building will include a new fine arts auditorium for university and community use, and is part of Liberty University's campus transformation initiative.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=63985 |title=New School of Music announced &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2012-09-14 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref><ref>[http://www2.newsadvance.com/news/2012/sep/17/new-school-music-announced-liberty-university-ar-2212999/ ]{{dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.wafb.com/story/19551385/new-liberty-university-school-of-music-announced ]{{dead link|date=February 2014}}</ref>

In the fall of 2014, Liberty University's School of Music will be adding several new degree programs, including Bachelor's degree concentrations in both Jazz Studies and Film Scoring (B.M.), and a 36 credit hour Master's degree in Music Education (M.A.). It has also been announced that the department is currently working on a new 45 credit hour Doctor of Worship Studies degree program (D.W.S.).

===Accreditation===
Liberty was founded in 1971 and received [[Southern Association of Colleges and Schools]] (SACS) accreditation in 1980,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacscoc.org/details.asp?instid=43000|title=Commission on Colleges: Institution Details|accessdate=2007-09-19}}</ref> which was most recently reaffirmed in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?PID=7650|title=About Liberty - Institutional and Program Accreditation|accessdate=2007-09-19}}</ref> In addition, it was accredited by the [[Transnational Association of Christian Colleges and Schools]] (TRACS) in September 1984, but resigned its TRACS accreditation on November 6, 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ope.ed.gov/accreditation/InstAccrDetails.aspx?756e697469643d3134373730332663616d70757349643d30267264743d352f32322f3230303920363a32313a343920504d|title= Accreditation Details: Liberty University|publisher=[[United States Department of Education]]|year=2009|first=|last=|accessdate= 2009-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tracs.org/files/DOE_Nov08.pdf|title=Commission Action November 2008|publisher=[[Transnational Association of Christian Colleges and Schools]]|date=November 2008|first=|last=|accessdate=2009-02-28}}</ref> Liberty has 60 accredited degree granting programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?PID=7650 |title=About Liberty &#124; Institutional and Program Accreditation &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2014-01-07 |accessdate=2015-04-16}}</ref> The law school, which opened in August 2004, gained provisional accreditation from the [[American Bar Association]] in 2006 and was granted full accreditation in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.catholic.org/college/story.php?id=37855|title=Liberty University School of Law Awarded Full Accreditation by the ABA}}</ref> On December 9, 2009, Chancellor Jerry Falwell Jr. announced that "Liberty University has received Level VI accreditation from the Southern Association of Colleges and Schools (SACS). This is the highest classification from SACS and is reserved for colleges and universities that offer four or more doctoral degrees.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?PID=18495&MID=13808 |title=News & Events - News Article - Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2009-12-10|accessdate=2010-12-17}}</ref> 
Liberty is also accredited by:
[[American Bar Association]] (ABA) <ref name="ReferenceB">{{cite web|url=http://www.liberty.edu/index.cfm?PID=7650 |title=About Liberty &#124; Institutional and Program Accreditation &#124; Liberty University |publisher=Liberty.edu |date=2014-02-04 |accessdate=2014-02-08}}</ref>
